)}}\n\n[[Category:LFF Lyga seasons]]\n[[Category:2007 in Lithuanian football|1]]\n[[Category:2007\u201308 in European association football leagues|Lith]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in European association football leagues|Lith]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eA Lyga", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_LFF_Lyga"}
{"title_page": "\u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = \u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai\n| native_name = \u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai\n| birth_name = Mai Nguyen Do\n| birth_place = [[Santa Clarita, California]]\n| occupation = Research & Policy Associate, [[Courage Campaign]]\n| language = English; Vietnamese\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| citizenship = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater = [[College of the Canyons]]\n| genre = [[Poetry]]\n| notableworks = Ghosts Still Walking, Battlefield Blooming\n| website = {{url|donguyenmai.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Mai Nguyen Do''', also known as '''\u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai''', is a Vietnamese American poet and activist from [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]], California. She attended [[College of the Canyons]] from where she received her associate degrees in history and the liberal arts and sciences.\n\nHer 2016 debut poetry collection ''Ghosts Still Walking'' was nominated by the members of the international Science Fiction and Fantasy Poetry Association for an Elgin Award for Book of the Year in 2017.<ref>[http://sfpoetry.com/el/17elgin.html 2017 Elgin Awards] Elgin Award Winners of the SFPA</ref>\n\n== Writing ==\n\u0110\u1ed7's poetry is influenced by her Vietnamese American identity and by her deep spiritual faith. When asked about influences on her writing, she has responded with several different sources of inspiration, including the words of ancient Vietnamese female writers and political figures like the [[Tr\u01b0ng Sisters|Tr\u01b0ng sisters]] and writers such as [[Murasaki Shikibu|Lady Murasaki]] and [[Frances Hodgson Burnett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://specpo.wordpress.com/2017/11/17/an-interview-with-do-nguyen-mai/|title=Ghosts Still Writing: An Interview with Do Nguyen Mai|website=SPECPO Science Fiction and Fantasy Poetry Association|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://youngstar.philstar.com/poet-rambutan-literary-editor-nguyen-mai-navigates-culture-living/|title=Poet and \u2018Rambutan Literary\u2019 editor Do Nguyen Mai navigates culture for a living|last=Pascual|first=Jam|date=March 30, 2017|work=Philippine Star Young Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHer debut poetry collection, ''Ghosts Still Walking,'' was published by [http://platypuspress.co.uk Platypus Press] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://platypuspress.co.uk/ghostsstillwalking|title=Ghosts Still Walking|website=Platypus Press}}</ref> Her second poetry collection, ''Battlefield Blooming,'' is scheduled to be released in spring of 2019 by Sahtu Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sahtupress.com/articles/battlefield-blooming-arriving-in-2019|title=Battlefield Blooming Arriving in 2019|date=December 14, 2018|website=Sahtu Press}}</ref> The release of ''Ghosts Still Walking'' was noted by Vietnamese language newspaper Viet Bao for its timely release on the anniversary of the [[Fall of Saigon]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vietbao.com/a252343/nha-tho-nu-goc-viet-16-tuoi-ra-mat-doc-tho-ngay-30-thang-tu-2016|title=Nh\u00e0 Th\u01a1 N\u1eef G\u1ed1c Vi\u1ec7t 16 Tu\u1ed5i Ra M\u1eaft, \u0110\u1ecdc Th\u01a1 ng\u00e0y 30 th\u00e1ng T\u01b0 2016|last=|first=|date=April 30, 2016|work=Viet Bao|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Political involvement ==\nAside from being a poet, \u0110\u1ed7 has been an ardent advocate for the arts and for Vietnamese American political and cultural development.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://saigoneer.com/saigon-music-art/12635-rambutan-literary-gives-voice-to-southeast-asians-at-home-and-abroad|title=In Rambutan Literary, a Home for Southeast Asian Voices From Around the Globe|last=Christiansen|first=Paul|date=March 5, 2018|work=Saigoneer|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> She often combines these lines of advocacy not only through community organizing and writing poetry, but also by being vocal on how issues such as immigration policy and police brutality have impacted the Southeast Asian American community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://signalscv.com/2018/05/mai-nguyen-do-my-fears-affirmed/|title=Mai Nguyen Do: My fears affirmed|last=Do|first=Mai|date=May 10, 2018|work=The Signal Santa Clarita Valley|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diacritics.org/2017/10/beneath-shroud-silence-tommy-les-death-shifts-focus-vietnamese-american-political-involvement/|title=From Beneath the Shroud of Silence: How Tommy Le's Death Shifts the Focus for Vietnamese American Political Involvement|last=Do|first=Mai|date=October 30, 2017|website=diaCRITICS|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was elected as an Assembly District Delegate to represent [[California's 38th State Assembly district|California's 38th Assembly District]] to the [[California Democratic Party]] on January 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cadem.org/our-party/adem/body/AD38-results.pdf|title=ADEM Preliminary Results, AD38|website=California Democratic Party|access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe currently works as the Research & Policy Associate for [[Courage Campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://couragecampaign.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Courage Campaign}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://saigoneer.com/saigon-music-art/12635-rambutan-literary-gives-voice-to-southeast-asians-at-home-and-abroad In Rambutan Literary, a Home for Southeast Asian Voices from Around the Globe \u2014 Paul Christiansen for Saigoneer, March 2018]\n* [http://donguyenmai.com Official website of Do Nguyen Mai]\n* [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/groundbreaking-asian-american-poets-read-immigrant-refugee-roots-n764211 'Groundbreaking' Asian-American Poets to Read With Immigrant, Refugee Roots \u2014 Frances Kai-Hwa Wang for NBC Asian America, May 2017]\n* [http://youngstar.philstar.com/poet-rambutan-literary-editor-nguyen-mai-navigates-culture-living/ Poet and \u2018Rambutan Literary\u2019 editor Do Nguyen Mai navigates culture for a living -- Jam Pascual for Philippine Star, Young Star, March 2017]\n* [https://vietbao.com/a252343/nha-tho-nu-goc-viet-16-tuoi-ra-mat-doc-tho-ngay-30-thang-tu-2016 Nh\u00e0 Th\u01a1 N\u1eef G\u1ed1c Vi\u1ec7t 16 Tu\u1ed5i Ra M\u1eaft, \u0110\u1ecdc Th\u01a1 ng\u00e0y 30 th\u00e1ng T\u01b0 2016 \u2014 Vi\u1ec7t B\u00e1o, April 2016]\n* [https://specpo.wordpress.com/2017/11/17/an-interview-with-do-nguyen-mai/ Ghosts Sill Writing: An Interview with Do Nguyen Mai, SPECPO]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:American people of Vietnamese descent]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:American writers of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:Asian-American literature]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:College of the Canyons alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name = \u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai\n| native_name = \u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai\n| birth_name = Mai Nguyen Do\n| birth_place = [[Santa Clarita, California]]\n| occupation = Research & Policy Associate, [[Courage Campaign]]\n| language = English; Vietnamese\n| nationality = [[United States]]\n| citizenship = [[United States]]\n| alma_mater = [[College of the Canyons]]\n| genre = [[Poetry]]\n| notableworks = Ghosts Still Walking, Battlefield Blooming\n| website = {{url|donguyenmai.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Mai Nguyen Do''', also known as '''\u0110\u1ed7 Nguy\u00ean Mai''', is a Vietnamese American poet and activist from [[Santa Clarita, California|Santa Clarita]], California. She attended [[College of the Canyons]] from where she received her associate degrees in history and the liberal arts and sciences. \n\nHer 2016 debut poetry collection ''Ghosts Still Walking'' was nominated by the members of the international Science Fiction and Fantasy Poetry Association for an Elgin Award for Book of the Year in 2017.<ref>[http://sfpoetry.com/el/17elgin.html 2017 Elgin Awards] Elgin Award Winners of the SFPA</ref> \n\n== Writing ==\n\u0110\u1ed7's poetry is influenced by her Vietnamese American identity and by her deep spiritual faith. When asked about influences on her writing, she has responded with several different sources of inspiration, including the words of ancient Vietnamese female writers and political figures like the [[Tr\u01b0ng Sisters|Tr\u01b0ng sisters]] and writers such as [[Murasaki Shikibu|Lady Murasaki]] and [[Frances Hodgson Burnett]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://specpo.wordpress.com/2017/11/17/an-interview-with-do-nguyen-mai/|title=Ghosts Still Writing: An Interview with Do Nguyen Mai|website=SPECPO Science Fiction and Fantasy Poetry Association|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://youngstar.philstar.com/poet-rambutan-literary-editor-nguyen-mai-navigates-culture-living/|title=Poet and \u2018Rambutan Literary\u2019 editor Do Nguyen Mai navigates culture for a living|last=Pascual|first=Jam|date=March 30, 2017|work=Philippine Star Young Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHer debut poetry collection, ''Ghosts Still Walking,'' was published by [http://platypuspress.co.uk Platypus Press] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://platypuspress.co.uk/ghostsstillwalking|title=Ghosts Still Walking|website=Platypus Press}}</ref> Her second poetry collection, ''Battlefield Blooming,'' is scheduled to be released in spring of 2019 by Sahtu Press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sahtupress.com/articles/battlefield-blooming-arriving-in-2019|title=Battlefield Blooming Arriving in 2019|date=December 14, 2018|website=Sahtu Press}}</ref> The release of ''Ghosts Still Walking'' was noted by Vietnamese language newspaper Viet Bao for its timely release on the anniversary of the [[Fall of Saigon]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://vietbao.com/a252343/nha-tho-nu-goc-viet-16-tuoi-ra-mat-doc-tho-ngay-30-thang-tu-2016|title=Nh\u00e0 Th\u01a1 N\u1eef G\u1ed1c Vi\u1ec7t 16 Tu\u1ed5i Ra M\u1eaft, \u0110\u1ecdc Th\u01a1 ng\u00e0y 30 th\u00e1ng T\u01b0 2016|last=|first=|date=April 30, 2016|work=Viet Bao|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Political involvement ==\nAside from being a poet, \u0110\u1ed7 has been an ardent advocate for the arts and for Vietnamese American political and cultural development.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://saigoneer.com/saigon-music-art/12635-rambutan-literary-gives-voice-to-southeast-asians-at-home-and-abroad|title=In Rambutan Literary, a Home for Southeast Asian Voices From Around the Globe|last=Christiansen|first=Paul|date=March 5, 2018|work=Saigoneer|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> She often combines these lines of advocacy not only through community organizing and writing poetry, but also by being vocal on how issues such as immigration policy and police brutality have impacted the Southeast Asian American community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://signalscv.com/2018/05/mai-nguyen-do-my-fears-affirmed/|title=Mai Nguyen Do: My fears affirmed|last=Do|first=Mai|date=May 10, 2018|work=The Signal Santa Clarita Valley|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://diacritics.org/2017/10/beneath-shroud-silence-tommy-les-death-shifts-focus-vietnamese-american-political-involvement/|title=From Beneath the Shroud of Silence: How Tommy Le's Death Shifts the Focus for Vietnamese American Political Involvement|last=Do|first=Mai|date=October 30, 2017|website=diaCRITICS|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe was elected as an Assembly District Delegate to represent [[California's 38th State Assembly district|California's 38th Assembly District]] to the [[California Democratic Party]] on January 27, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cadem.org/our-party/adem/body/AD38-results.pdf|title=ADEM Preliminary Results, AD38|website=California Democratic Party|access-date=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nShe currently works as the Research & Policy Associate for [[Courage Campaign]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://couragecampaign.org/who-we-are|title=Who We Are|website=Courage Campaign}}</ref>  \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://saigoneer.com/saigon-music-art/12635-rambutan-literary-gives-voice-to-southeast-asians-at-home-and-abroad In Rambutan Literary, a Home for Southeast Asian Voices from Around the Globe \u2014 Paul Christiansen for Saigoneer, March 2018]\n* [http://donguyenmai.com Official website of Do Nguyen Mai]\n* [https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/groundbreaking-asian-american-poets-read-immigrant-refugee-roots-n764211 'Groundbreaking' Asian-American Poets to Read With Immigrant, Refugee Roots \u2014 Frances Kai-Hwa Wang for NBC Asian America, May 2017]\n* [http://youngstar.philstar.com/poet-rambutan-literary-editor-nguyen-mai-navigates-culture-living/ Poet and \u2018Rambutan Literary\u2019 editor Do Nguyen Mai navigates culture for a living -- Jam Pascual for Philippine Star, Young Star, March 2017]\n* [https://vietbao.com/a252343/nha-tho-nu-goc-viet-16-tuoi-ra-mat-doc-tho-ngay-30-thang-tu-2016 Nh\u00e0 Th\u01a1 N\u1eef G\u1ed1c Vi\u1ec7t 16 Tu\u1ed5i Ra M\u1eaft, \u0110\u1ecdc Th\u01a1 ng\u00e0y 30 th\u00e1ng T\u01b0 2016 \u2014 Vi\u1ec7t B\u00e1o, April 2016]\n* [https://specpo.wordpress.com/2017/11/17/an-interview-with-do-nguyen-mai/ Ghosts Sill Writing: An Interview with Do Nguyen Mai, SPECPO]\n\n[[Category:American people of Vietnamese descent]]\n[[Category:American women writers]]\n[[Category:American writers of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:Asian-American literature]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:College of the Canyons alumni]]\n[[Category:Washington College alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{US-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%90%E1%BB%97_Nguy%C3%AAn_Mai"}
{"title_page": "Nicole Maurey", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = Nicole Maurey.jpg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1925|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Bois-Colombes]], [[Hauts-de-Seine]], [[\u00cele-de-France (region)|\u00cele-de-France]], France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2016|3|11|1925|12|20}}\n| death_place = [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], France\n| spouse      = Jacques L. Gallo (1950\u20131960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/613/Nicole+Maurey/register.php|title=Nicole Maurey - The Private Life and Times of Nicole Maurey. Nicole Maurey Pictures.|website=www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com}}</ref>\n| yearsactive = 1945&ndash;1997\n| website     = http://nicole.maurey.site.voila.fr/\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Maurey''' (20 December 1925 &ndash; 11 March 2016) was a French actress, who appeared in 65 film and television productions between 1945 and 1997.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=Biography for Nicole Maurey |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0561072/bio |publisher=IMDB |accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> \n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Bois-Colombes]], a northwestern suburb of Paris, Maurey was originally a dancer before being cast in her first film role in 1944.<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\nIn 1953 Maurey appeared opposite [[Bing Crosby]] in ''[[Little Boy Lost (1953 film)|Little Boy Lost]]'' that was filmed in France.  The following year [[Universal-International]] brought Nicole Maurey from France, [[Gia Scala]] from Italy and Myriam Verbeeck from Belgium to the United States to test for the role of [[Mary Magdelene]] in an unproduced [[Biblical epic]] ''The Galileans''<ref>p. 42 ''LIFE'' 8 Nov 1954</ref>.   She remains most noted as [[Charlton Heston]]'s [[leading lady]] in ''[[Secret of the Incas]]'' (1954), often cited as the primary inspiration for ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981). She starred in films with [[Alec Guinness]], [[Bette Davis]], [[Bing Crosby]], [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]], [[Fess Parker]], [[Rex Harrison]], [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]] and [[Mickey Rooney]], among numerous others. She was the leading lady in the original 1962 [[science fiction]] cult film ''[[The Day of the Triffids (film)|The Day of the Triffids]]''. Later in life, she moved into television, appearing in various made-for-TV movies and mini-series.\n\nShe was married to Jacques Gallo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=Vernon|title=Nicole Maurey Tells How To Snag a Husband|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5739148/valley_morning_star/|work=Valley Morning Star|agency=United Press|date=September 8, 1953|location=Texas, Harlingen|page=10|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 30, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nMaurey died in March 2016 at the age of 90.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlton-heston.net/nicole-maurey-est-decedee-le-11-mars-2016-a125560164 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408233126/http://www.charlton-heston.net/nicole-maurey-est-decedee-le-11-mars-2016-a125560164 |archivedate=2016-04-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Le Cavalier noir (1945 film)|Le cavalier noir]]'' (1945) as Solange\n* ''[[Pamela (film)|Pamela]]'' (1945, directed by [[Pierre de H\u00e9rain]]) as Mme Royale\n* ''[[Blondine]]'' (1945) as Blondine\n* ''[[La bataille du feu]]'' (1949) as Anne-Marie\n* ''[[Diary of a Country Priest|Journal d'un cur\u00e9 de campagne]]'' (1951) as Mlle Louise\n* ''[[Rendezvous in Grenada]]'' (1951) Manina\n* ''[[Le dernier Robin des Bois]]'' (1953) as Isabelle Delorme\n* ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Op\u00e9ration Magali|fr}}'' (1953) as Manon\n* ''[[Les Compagnes de la nuit]]'' (1953) as Yvonne Leriche\n* ''[[L'oeil en coulisse]]'' (1953) as Annette Durand\n* ''[[Little Boy Lost (1953 film)|Little Boy Lost]]'' (1953) as Lisa Garret\n* ''[[L'Ennemi public num\u00e9ro un]]'' (1953) as Peggy\n* ''[[Si Versailles m'\u00e9tait cont\u00e9...]]'' (1954) as Mademoiselle de Fontanges\n* ''[[Secret of the Incas]]'' (1954) as Elena Antonescu\n* ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1955 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'' (1955) as [[Mme Tallien]] (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Constant Husband]]'' (1955) as Lola\n* ''[[The Bold and the Brave]]'' (1956) as Fiamma\n* ''[[The Weapon (film)|The Weapon]]'' (1956) as Vivienne\n* ''[[Section des disparus]]'' (1956) as Diana Lander\n* ''[[Action imm\u00e9diate (film, 1957)|Action imm\u00e9diate]]'' (1957) as Diana Rossi\n* ''[[Rogue's Yarn]]'' (1957) as Michele Cartier\n* ''[[Me and the Colonel]]'' (1958) as Suzanne Roualet\n* ''[[The Scapegoat (1959 film)|The Scapegoat]]'' (1959) as Bela\n* ''[[The Jayhawkers!]]'' (1959) (aka ''Violence au Kansas'') as Jeanne Dubois\n* ''[[The House of the Seven Hawks]]'' (1959) as Constanta Sluiter\n* ''[[High Time (film)|High Time]]'' (1960) as Prof. Helene Gauthier\n* ''[[His and Hers (film)|His and Hers]]'' (1961) as Simone Rolfe\n* ''[[Don't Bother to Knock (1961 film)|Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1961) as Lucille\n* ''[[The Day of the Triffids (film)|The Day of the Triffids]]'' (1963) as Christine Durrant\n* ''[[The Very Edge]]'' (1963) as Helen\n* ''[[Pleins feux sur Stanislas]]'' (1965) as Claire\n* ''[[Sale temps pour les mouches]]'' (1966) as Eva Delagrange\n* ''[[Gloria (film, 1977)|Gloria]]'' (1977) as Alice\n* ''[[Chanel Solitaire]]'' (1981) as Grande Dame\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Television===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'' (1955, Episode: \"Tomorrow We'll Love\") as Denise\n* ''[[Casablanca (1955 TV series)|Casablanca]]'' (1955, Episode: \"Black Market Operation\") as Denise\n* ''[[Avatar (1964 film)|Avatar]]'' (1964, TV Movie)\n* ''[[Rouletabille]]'' (1966, Episode: \"Le parfum de la dame en noir\") as Mathilde Stengerson\n* ''[[La Morale de l'histoire]]'' (1966, TV Movie) as Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* ''[[Champion House]]'' (1967) as Michele Champion\n* ''[[No\u00eblle aux quatre vents]]'' (1970) as Lisette Andrieux\n* ''[[Mon seul amour]]'' (1971) as Claude\n* ''[[La Demoiselle d'Avignon]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Nicole\n* ''[[Les \u00c9vasions c\u00e9l\u00e8bres]]'' (1972) as Mme de Boislinard\n* ''[[Le grillon du foyer]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Dot\n* ''[[La vie et la passion de Dodin-Bouffant]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Pauline\n* ''[[Au th\u00e9\u00e2tre ce soir]]'' (1972, Episode: \"[[Histoire d'un d\u00e9tective]]\") as Mary McLaren\n* ''[[Les nuits de la col\u00e8re]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Louise\n* ''[[Le provocateur]]'' (1973) as Gis\u00e8le Charmoy\n* ''[[Une atroce petite musique]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Ir\u00e8ne Musselet\n* ''[[Marie Dorval]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Mademoiselle Mars\n* ''[[Les \u00e9crivains]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Eve\n* ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph Balsamo (miniseries)|fr|3=Joseph Balsamo (mini-s\u00e9rie)|lt=Joseph Balsamo}}'' (1973, TV Mini-Series) as Frau Grammont (uncredited)\n* ''[[Lucien Leuwen]]'' (1973-1974, TV Mini-Series) as Mme Leuwen\n* ''[[Au th\u00e9\u00e2tre ce soir]]'' (1974, Episode: \"[[Le proc\u00e8s de Mary Dugan]]\") as Mme Rice\n* ''[[La Passag\u00e8re (t\u00e9l\u00e9film)|La passag\u00e8re]]'' (1974, TV Movie) as Catherine Caron\n* ''[[Comme du bon pain]]'' (1976, TV Mini-Series) as Madeleine Rivard\n* ''[[La lune papa]]'' (1977, TV Mini-Series) as Mme Marchandou\n* ''[[La vie des autres]]'' (1980) as Blanche\n* ''[[Sunday Night Thriller]]'' (1981, Episode: \"I Thought They Died Years Ago\") as Eliane Label\n* ''[[Marianne, une \u00e9toile pour Napol\u00e9on]]'' (1983) as Princesse de Benevent\n* ''[[Les Cinq Derni\u00e8res Minutes]]'' (1983) as Gertrude Necken\n* ''[[Rouge Marine]]'' (1983) as Gertrude Necken\n* ''[[Coulisses]]'' (1986) as Sabine Corval\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Theater==\n* 1952: ''[[Harvey (play)|Harvey]]'' by [[Mary Chase (playwright)|Mary Chase]], director [[Marcel Achard]], [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Antoine]]\n* 1964: ''La Preuve par quatre'' written and directed by [[F\u00e9licien Marceau]], [[Th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Michodi\u00e8re]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0561072|name=Nicole Maurey}}\n* {{Amg name|46574}}\n* [http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/613/Nicole+Maurey/index.html The Private Life and Times of Nicole Maurey]\n* \n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maurey, Nicole}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bois-Colombes]]\n[[Category:French film actresses]]\n[[Category:French television actresses]]\n[[Category:French female dancers]]\n[[Category:20th-century French actresses]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the French National Academy of Dramatic Arts]]\n[[Category:French expatriate actresses in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       = Nicole Maurey.jpg\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1925|12|20}}\n| birth_place = [[Bois-Colombes]], [[Hauts-de-Seine]], [[\u00cele-de-France (region)|\u00cele-de-France]], France\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|2016|3|11|1925|12|20}}\n| death_place = [[Versailles, Yvelines|Versailles]], France\n| spouse      = Jacques L. Gallo (1950\u20131960)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com/show/613/Nicole+Maurey/register.php|title=Nicole Maurey - The Private Life and Times of Nicole Maurey. Nicole Maurey Pictures.|website=www.glamourgirlsofthesilverscreen.com}}</ref>\n| yearsactive = 1945&ndash;1997\n| website     = http://nicole.maurey.site.voila.fr/\n}}\n\n'''Nicole Maurey''' (20 December 1925 &ndash; 11 March 2016) was a French actress, who appeared in 65 film and television productions between 1945 and 1997.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=Biography for Nicole Maurey |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0561072/bio |publisher=IMDB |accessdate=2009-02-21}}</ref> \n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Bois-Colombes]], a northwestern suburb of Paris, Maurey was originally a dancer before being cast in her first film role in 1944.<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\nIn 1953 Maurey appeared opposite [[Bing Crosby]] in ''[[Little Boy Lost (1953 film)|Little Boy Lost]]'' that was filmed in France.  The following year [[Universal-International]] brought Nicole Maurey from France, [[Gia Scala]] from Italy and Myriam Verbeeck from Belgium to the United States to test for the role of [[Mary Magdelene]] in an unproduced [[Biblical epic]] ''The Galileans''<ref>p. 42 ''LIFE'' 8 Nov 1954</ref>.   She remains most noted as [[Charlton Heston]]'s [[leading lady]] in ''[[Secret of the Incas]]'' (1954), often cited as the primary inspiration for ''[[Raiders of the Lost Ark]]'' (1981). She starred in films with [[Alec Guinness]], [[Bette Davis]], [[Bing Crosby]], [[Jeff Chandler (actor)|Jeff Chandler]], [[Fess Parker]], [[Rex Harrison]], [[Robert Taylor (actor)|Robert Taylor]] and [[Mickey Rooney]], among numerous others. She was the leading lady in the original 1962 [[science fiction]] cult film ''[[The Day of the Triffids (film)|The Day of the Triffids]]''. Later in life, she moved into television, appearing in various made-for-TV movies and mini-series.\n\nShe was married to Jacques Gallo.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scott|first1=Vernon|title=Nicole Maurey Tells How To Snag a Husband|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5739148/valley_morning_star/|work=Valley Morning Star|agency=United Press|date=September 8, 1953|location=Texas, Harlingen|page=10|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = June 30, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\nMaurey died in March 2016 at the age of 90.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.charlton-heston.net/nicole-maurey-est-decedee-le-11-mars-2016-a125560164 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160408233126/http://www.charlton-heston.net/nicole-maurey-est-decedee-le-11-mars-2016-a125560164 |archivedate=2016-04-08 }}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Le Cavalier noir (1945 film)|Le cavalier noir]]'' (1945) as Solange\n* ''[[Pamela (film)|Pamela]]'' (1945, directed by [[Pierre de H\u00e9rain]]) as Mme Royale\n* ''[[Blondine]]'' (1945) as Blondine\n* ''[[La bataille du feu]]'' (1949) as Anne-Marie\n* ''[[Diary of a Country Priest|Journal d'un cur\u00e9 de campagne]]'' (1951) as Mlle Louise\n* ''[[Rendezvous in Grenada]]'' (1951) Manina\n* ''[[Le dernier Robin des Bois]]'' (1953) as Isabelle Delorme\n* ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Op\u00e9ration Magali|fr}}'' (1953) as Manon\n* ''[[Les Compagnes de la nuit]]'' (1953) as Yvonne Leriche\n* ''[[L'oeil en coulisse]]'' (1953) as Annette Durand\n* ''[[Little Boy Lost (1953 film)|Little Boy Lost]]'' (1953) as Lisa Garret\n* ''[[L'Ennemi public num\u00e9ro un]]'' (1953) as Peggy\n* ''[[Si Versailles m'\u00e9tait cont\u00e9...]]'' (1954) as Mademoiselle de Fontanges\n* ''[[Secret of the Incas]]'' (1954) as Elena Antonescu\n* ''[[Napol\u00e9on (1955 film)|Napol\u00e9on]]'' (1955) as [[Mme Tallien]] (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Constant Husband]]'' (1955) as Lola\n* ''[[The Bold and the Brave]]'' (1956) as Fiamma\n* ''[[The Weapon (film)|The Weapon]]'' (1956) as Vivienne\n* ''[[Section des disparus]]'' (1956) as Diana Lander\n* ''[[Action imm\u00e9diate (film, 1957)|Action imm\u00e9diate]]'' (1957) as Diana Rossi\n* ''[[Rogue's Yarn]]'' (1957) as Michele Cartier\n* ''[[Me and the Colonel]]'' (1958) as Suzanne Roualet\n* ''[[The Scapegoat (1959 film)|The Scapegoat]]'' (1959) as Bela\n* ''[[The Jayhawkers!]]'' (1959) (aka ''Violence au Kansas'') as Jeanne Dubois\n* ''[[The House of the Seven Hawks]]'' (1959) as Constanta Sluiter\n* ''[[High Time (film)|High Time]]'' (1960) as Prof. Helene Gauthier\n* ''[[His and Hers (film)|His and Hers]]'' (1961) as Simone Rolfe\n* ''[[Don't Bother to Knock (1961 film)|Don't Bother to Knock]]'' (1961) as Lucille\n* ''[[The Day of the Triffids (film)|The Day of the Triffids]]'' (1963) as Christine Durrant\n* ''[[The Very Edge]]'' (1963) as Helen\n* ''[[Pleins feux sur Stanislas]]'' (1965) as Claire\n* ''[[Sale temps pour les mouches]]'' (1966) as Eva Delagrange\n* ''[[Gloria (film, 1977)|Gloria]]'' (1977) as Alice\n* ''[[Chanel Solitaire]]'' (1981) as Grande Dame\n{{Div col end}}\n\n===Television===\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'' (1955, Episode: \"Tomorrow We'll Love\") as Denise\n* ''[[Casablanca (1955 TV series)|Casablanca]]'' (1955, Episode: \"Black Market Operation\") as Denise\n* ''[[Avatar (1964 film)|Avatar]]'' (1964, TV Movie)\n* ''[[Rouletabille]]'' (1966, Episode: \"Le parfum de la dame en noir\") as Mathilde Stengerson\n* ''[[La Morale de l'histoire]]'' (1966, TV Movie) as Th\u00e9r\u00e8se\n* ''[[Champion House]]'' (1967) as Michele Champion\n* ''[[No\u00eblle aux quatre vents]]'' (1970) as Lisette Andrieux\n* ''[[Mon seul amour]]'' (1971) as Claude\n* ''[[La Demoiselle d'Avignon]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Nicole\n* ''[[Les \u00c9vasions c\u00e9l\u00e8bres]]'' (1972) as Mme de Boislinard\n* ''[[Le grillon du foyer]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Dot\n* ''[[La vie et la passion de Dodin-Bouffant]]'' (1972, TV Movie) as Pauline\n* ''[[Au th\u00e9\u00e2tre ce soir]]'' (1972, Episode: \"[[Histoire d'un d\u00e9tective]]\") as Mary McLaren\n* ''[[Les nuits de la col\u00e8re]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Louise\n* ''[[Le provocateur]]'' (1973) as Gis\u00e8le Charmoy\n* ''[[Une atroce petite musique]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Ir\u00e8ne Musselet\n* ''[[Marie Dorval]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Mademoiselle Mars\n* ''[[Les \u00e9crivains]]'' (1973, TV Movie) as Eve\n* ''{{Interlanguage link multi|Joseph Balsamo (miniseries)|fr|3=Joseph Balsamo (mini-s\u00e9rie)|lt=Joseph Balsamo}}'' (1973, TV Mini-Series) as Frau Grammont (uncredited)\n* ''[[Lucien Leuwen]]'' (1973-1974, TV Mini-Series) as Mme Leuwen\n* ''[[Au th\u00e9\u00e2tre ce soir]]'' (1974, Episode: \"[[Le proc\u00e8s de Mary Dugan]]\") as Mme Rice\n* ''[[La Passag\u00e8re (t\u00e9l\u00e9film)|La passag\u00e8re]]'' (1974, TV Movie) as Catherine Caron\n* ''[[Comme du bon pain]]'' (1976, TV Mini-Series) as Madeleine Rivard\n* ''[[La lune papa]]'' (1977, TV Mini-Seri