{"title_page": "Angela Maria Autsch", "text_new": "{{short description|German nun}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name          = [[Venerable]]<br>Angela Maria Autsch<br>[[Trinitarian Sisters of Valence|C.S.S.T.]]\n|image         = Angela Autsch.jpg\n|imagesize     =\n|caption       =\n|titles=Religious\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1900|03|26}}\n|birth_place   = [[R\u00f6llecken]], [[Attendorn]], [[German Empire]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1944|12|23|1900|05|26}}\n|death_place   = [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]], [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German-occupied Poland]]\n|feast_day     =\n|venerated_in  = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|suppressed_date=\n|baptized_date =\n}}\n\n'''Angela Maria of the Heart of Jesus''', also called '''Angela Maria Autsch''', baptized as '''Maria Cecilia Autsch''' (26 March 1900 \u2013 23 December 1944),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heiligenlexikon.de/BiographienA/Angela_Autsch.html|title=Angela vom Heiligen Herzen Jesu Autsch - \u00d6kumenisches Heiligenlexikon|website=www.heiligenlexikon.de|language=de|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> was a German Trinitarian Sister of Valencia, and [[Roman Catholic]] [[Venerable]].\n\n== Biography ==\nMaria Cecilia Autsch was born in R\u00f6llecken, part of [[Attendorn]] in the [[Olpe (district)|Olpe district]] of ([[Westphalia]]), [[German Empire]] on March 26, 1900. She was a member of a modest working-class family (her father was a quarry worker) that regularly practised the Catholic faith. She went to school in the village of Bamenohl. The terrible economic situation in the [[Weimar Republic]] meant that she had to go out to work in the clothing store Bischoff & Broegger in [[Finnentrop]], where she was popular amongst both fellow workers and customers\n\nMaria was thirty-three years old when she joined the Trinitarian Sisters of Valencia in [[M\u00f6tz]], [[Austria]]. She began the novitiate and was given the name Angela Maria of the Sacred Heart of Jesus. The novitiate ended with the first profession of vows on August 16, 1934. Her final profession took place on September 28, 1938, the year Hitler annexed Austria.\n\nOn the morning of August 10, 1940, Sr Angela went to buy some milk. She happened to meet some women she knew at the dairy and, conversing with them, she related that  the Allies had sunk a German ship off Norway and many had died in that disaster. She ended saying ''Hitler is a calamity for Europe''.<ref>Anthony O. D'Errico, ''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997, 421.</ref> One of the women, a known Nazi sympathizer, related to her son, also a Nazi sympathizer, what she had heard from Sr. Angela. He reported the fact to the chief of the [[Gestapo]].\n\nThe Gestapo opened a file on Sr. Angela and arrested her on August 12, 1940. She was jailed for seventeen days in Innsbruck before becoming prisoner no. 4651 in the concentration camp of [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp|Ravensbr\u00fcck]] on August 31, 1940. There she was a light of hope and courage to her fellow inmates. She was frequently beaten by her captors but her contagious good humor was \"a ray of sunshine in deepest Hell\". Some prisoners who might have killed themselves were inspired by her, they said afterwards, even those who had no idea that she was a nun.<ref>Anthony O. D'Errico, ''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997, 422-423.</ref>\n\nThe Nazis sent Sr. Angela to Auschwitz where she befriended a Jewish woman doctor from Slovakia, Margarita Schwalbova. Feeling depressed and less than human, she was deeply moved when the nun went up to her and gently stroked her hair. Although Schwalbova was an atheist, she and Sister Angela became friends, with the latter acting in a way that earned her the title ''Angel of Auschwitz''.<ref>Gaston V\u00e9lez de Mendizabal, ''Verzehrendes Feuer: Sr. Angela Maria Autsch, der Engel von Auschwitz'', Maria Roggendorf, 1997, p. 13.</ref> When Schwalbova was sick, she told her stories about the lives and miracles of the saints, shared her meager rations with her and others even though this was strictly forbidden. In March 1943, Sister Angela was transferred to Birkenau another camp where she worked in the kitchen and infirmary, caring equally for inmates and persecutors. She died on December 23, 1944, during an Allied air raid whilst taking care of patients and her body was cremated just a month before the Allies liberated the camp.\n\nHer cause for [[beatification]] was introduced by the Conference of Austrian Bishops on March 26, 1992. She was declared [[The Venerable|venerable]] by [[Pope Francis]] on May 19, 2018, upon the confirmation of her [[heroic virtue]] practiced during her life.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Anthony O. D'Errico,''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997.\n* Gaston V\u00e9lez de Mendizabal: ''Verzehrendes Feuer: Sr. Angela Maria Autsch, der Engel von Auschwitz'', Maria Roggendorf, 1997\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Saints|Biography|Catholicism|World War II|Germany}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autsch, Angela Maria}}\n[[Category:Trinitarians]]\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:German nuns]]\n[[Category:German people who died in Auschwitz concentration camp]]\n[[Category:German Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Venerated Catholics by Pope Francis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German nun}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name          = [[Venerable]]<br>Angela Maria Autsch<br>[[Trinitarian Sisters of Valence|C.S.S.T.]]\n|image         = Angela Autsch.jpg\n|imagesize     =\n|caption       =\n|titles=Religious\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1900|05|26}}\n|birth_place   = [[R\u00f6llecken]], [[Attendorn]], [[German Empire]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1944|12|23|1900|05|26}}\n|death_place   = [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]], [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u20131945)|German-occupied Poland]]\n|feast_day     =\n|venerated_in  = [[Roman Catholic Church]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|suppressed_date=\n|baptized_date =\n}}\n\n'''Angela Maria of the Heart of Jesus''', also called '''Angela Maria Autsch''', baptized as '''Maria Cecilia Autsch''' (26 March 1900 \u2013 23 December 1944),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heiligenlexikon.de/BiographienA/Angela_Autsch.html|title=Angela vom Heiligen Herzen Jesu Autsch - \u00d6kumenisches Heiligenlexikon|website=www.heiligenlexikon.de|language=de|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref> was a German Trinitarian Sister of Valencia, and [[Roman Catholic]] [[Venerable]].\n\n== Biography ==\nMaria Cecilia Autsch was born in R\u00f6llecken, part of [[Attendorn]] in the [[Olpe (district)|Olpe district]] of ([[Westphalia]]), [[German Empire]] on March 26, 1900. She was a member of a modest working-class family (her father was a quarry worker) that regularly practised the Catholic faith. She went to school in the village of Bamenohl. The terrible economic situation in the [[Weimar Republic]] meant that she had to go out to work in the clothing store Bischoff & Broegger in [[Finnentrop]], where she was popular amongst both fellow workers and customers\n\nMaria was thirty-three years old when she joined the Trinitarian Sisters of Valencia in [[M\u00f6tz]], [[Austria]]. She began the novitiate and was given the name Angela Maria of the Sacred Heart of Jesus. The novitiate ended with the first profession of vows on August 16, 1934. Her final profession took place on September 28, 1938, the year Hitler annexed Austria.\n\nOn the morning of August 10, 1940, Sr Angela went to buy some milk. She happened to meet some women she knew at the dairy and, conversing with them, she related that  the Allies had sunk a German ship off Norway and many had died in that disaster. She ended saying ''Hitler is a calamity for Europe''.<ref>Anthony O. D'Errico, ''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997, 421.</ref> One of the women, a known Nazi sympathizer, related to her son, also a Nazi sympathizer, what she had heard from Sr. Angela. He reported the fact to the chief of the [[Gestapo]].\n\nThe Gestapo opened a file on Sr. Angela and arrested her on August 12, 1940. She was jailed for seventeen days in Innsbruck before becoming prisoner no. 4651 in the concentration camp of [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp|Ravensbr\u00fcck]] on August 31, 1940. There she was a light of hope and courage to her fellow inmates. She was frequently beaten by her captors but her contagious good humor was \"a ray of sunshine in deepest Hell\". Some prisoners who might have killed themselves were inspired by her, they said afterwards, even those who had no idea that she was a nun.<ref>Anthony O. D'Errico, ''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997, 422-423.</ref>\n\nThe Nazis sent Sr. Angela to Auschwitz where she befriended a Jewish woman doctor from Slovakia, Margarita Schwalbova. Feeling depressed and less than human, she was deeply moved when the nun went up to her and gently stroked her hair. Although Schwalbova was an atheist, she and Sister Angela became friends, with the latter acting in a way that earned her the title ''Angel of Auschwitz''.<ref>Gaston V\u00e9lez de Mendizabal, ''Verzehrendes Feuer: Sr. Angela Maria Autsch, der Engel von Auschwitz'', Maria Roggendorf, 1997, p. 13.</ref> When Schwalbova was sick, she told her stories about the lives and miracles of the saints, shared her meager rations with her and others even though this was strictly forbidden. In March 1943, Sister Angela was transferred to Birkenau another camp where she worked in the kitchen and infirmary, caring equally for inmates and persecutors. She died on December 23, 1944, during an Allied air raid whilst taking care of patients and her body was cremated just a month before the Allies liberated the camp.\n\nHer cause for [[beatification]] was introduced by the Conference of Austrian Bishops on March 26, 1992. She was declared [[The Venerable|venerable]] by [[Pope Francis]] on May 19, 2018, upon the confirmation of her [[heroic virtue]] practiced during her life.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* Anthony O. D'Errico,''The Trinitarians'', Roma, 1997.\n* Gaston V\u00e9lez de Mendizabal: ''Verzehrendes Feuer: Sr. Angela Maria Autsch, der Engel von Auschwitz'', Maria Roggendorf, 1997\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Saints|Biography|Catholicism|World War II|Germany}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autsch, Angela Maria}}\n[[Category:Trinitarians]]\n[[Category:1900 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:German nuns]]\n[[Category:German people who died in Auschwitz concentration camp]]\n[[Category:German Servants of God]]\n[[Category:Venerated Catholics by Pope Francis]]\n", "name_user": "Ayyeeitsalexx", "label": "safe", "comment": "The birth date said May 26, when it's actually March 26", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angela_Maria_Autsch"}
{"title_page": "\u0110uro Arnold", "text_new": "[[File:\u0110uro Arnold 1898 Povjest knji\u017eevnosti hrvatske i srpske.png|thumb|\u0110uro Arnold]]\n'''\u0110uro Arnold''' (24 March 1853 \u2013 22 February 1941) was a [[Croatia]]n writer and [[philosopher]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://proleksis.lzmk.hr/8207/ |contribution=Arnold, \u0110uro |title=[[Proleksis Encyclopedia]] |date=September 2013 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and study==\nArnold was born as the 19th of 24 children of Ivan, a [[tax gatherer]], and Sofija, n\u00e9e [[Vukani\u0107]]. His ancestors arrived from [[Switzerland]] during the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"HBL\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://hbl.lzmk.hr/clanak.aspx?id=856 |contribution=ARNOLD, \u0110uro |last=Flego |first=Vi\u0161nja |author-link=Vi\u0161nja Flego |last2=Kaminski |first2=Martin |author2-link=Martin Kaminski |title=[[Croatian Biographical Lexicon]] |year=1983 |volume=1 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref> He was born in [[Ivanec]] and spent his early childhood in [[Krapina]]. He attended [[primary school]] in [[Zagreb]], and high school in [[Vara\u017edin]] and Zagreb, where he graduated in 1873.\n\nIn 1874 he enrolled at the [[Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb]] majoring in [[philosophy]], with a minor in [[history]] and [[geography]]. During the [[Bosnian crisis]] he was recruited, and it was only in 1879 that he was hired as a professor in a Zagreb [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]]. In 1880 he was promoted as the first PhD in philosophy at the [[University of Zagreb]], with a thesis ''Ethics and history'' (''Etika i povijest''), which was published in 1879.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> He continued his studies at the universities of [[University of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] (1880), Berlin and Paris (1881/1882).\n\n== Work ==\nSince 1889 he served as the Director of the Royal Teacher's School. In 1894 he was appointed as a professor extraordinarius, and since 1896 as the full professor of theoretical and practical philosophy and pedagogy at the [[Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb]]. He retired in 1923. He was the dean of the Faculty of Arts in the periods of 1898\u20131899, and 1912\u20131913, and also the rector of the [[University of Zagreb]] in the period 1899\u20131900.\n\nHe was appointed as a corresponding member of the [[Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts]] in 1891, and as a full member in 1899. He served as the president of [[Matica hrvatska]] in 1902\u20131909. In 1892 he became an honorary member of the Croatian Pedagogic-Literary Society, in 1924 a member of the Society of the Brothers of the Croatian Dragon, and an [[honorary citizen]] of [[Krapina]].<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\n==Writer==\nAs a writer, his work is a continuation of Croatia's romantic poetry in the tradition of [[August \u0160enoa]] and [[Franjo Markovi\u0107]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/> His first appearance as a writer was the song ''Pri povratku'' (\"On the way back\", ''Vienac'', 1873, 49). He mostly published patriotic songs, romances and [[ballad]]s with themes from [[Croatian history]] and [[folklore]] (''Krapinske elegije'', ''Damjan Juda, knez dubrova\u010dki'', ''Kata Lovi\u0107eva'' etc.), as well as reflexive lyricism in publications such as [[Vienac]] (1873\u20131886, 1888\u20131891, 1893\u20131902 ), [[Hrvatska lipa]] (1875), [[Hrvatski dom]] (1876), [[Obzor]] (1898, 1900, 1901, 1904), [[Prosvjeta]] (1904\u20131913), [[Hrvatsko kolo]] (1905, 1906, 1908, 1930), [[Katoli\u010dki list]] (1906, 1915, 1916), [[Hrvatska smotra]] (1907\u20131910, 1933), [[Hrvatsko pravo]] (1908, 1924), [[Koledar hrvatskoga katoli\u010dkoga narodnoga \u0111a\u0161tva]] (1909, 1910), [[Serafinski perivoj]] (1909\u20131913), [[Knji\u017eevni prilog]] (1911, 1912, 1913\u20131915), [[Hrvatska (publication)|Hrvatska]] (1912, 1914, 1915), [[Hrvatska prosvjeta]] (1914\u20131918), [[Na\u0161a misao]] (1914, 1915 ), [[Jeka od Osijeka]] (1918, 1919), [[Vijenac]] (1923, 1925, 1927), [[Hrvatsko pravo]] (1924, 1925), [[Omladina]] (1924, 1925), [[Hranilovi\u0107eva spomenica]] (1925), [[Selo i grad]] (1928/1929, 1930, 1931), [[Hrvatski list]] (1939), [[Novo doba]] (1940) and others. He wrote a single short story ''Samo \u010detvrt sata'' (Vienac, 1880, 15\u201318).<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nHe signed his works in codes and pseudonyms: ''A.'', ''G. A.'', ''Gj. A.'', ''Gj. A-d'', ''Gj. Ar.'', ''O. D.'', ''R. R.'', ''Ivan\u010danin'', ''Georg Arnold''.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> He published several books of poems, and the poem ''Domovina'' has gained him popularity.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> His works were published in many anthologies, calendars and almanacs. The selection of his poetry was translated to [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Esperanto]], [[German language|German]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]] and [[Italian language|Italian]]. He expressed his views on literature in talks at the Matica hrvatska conferences: ''Umjetnost prema znanosti'', ''Mo\u017ee li umjetnost zamijeniti vjeru'', ''Jedinstvena hrvatska narodna kultura'' (Glas Matice hrvatske, 1906, 1908, 1909).<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\n==Philosopher==\nAs a philosopher, he was influenced by [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]], [[Johann Friedrich Herbart]] and [[Hermann Lotze]], representing the \"spiritualist positivism\" movement and the view that the knowledge of the world can be reached only by the combined efforts of [[science]], [[art]] and [[religion]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/>  He wrote on the fundamental questions of philosophy, which he defined as the science of \"final causes and purposes of being\".<ref>''Logika'', p. 40</ref>\n\nIn the treatise ''Zadnja bi\u0107a'' (\"Last beings\", Rad JAZU, 1888, 93 ) he conceived a world composed from the variety of simple, immutable soullike \"last beings\" that are connected by the feeling of touch and hierarchically arranged according to different levels of awareness, with absolute consciousness, the [[God]], occupying the peak of the hierarchy.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> According to Arnold, faith represents the supreme stronghold of a man and the basic principle of harmony of his spiritual functions.<ref name=\"HE\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://www.enciklopedija.hr/Natuknica.aspx?ID=3953 |contribution=Arnold, \u0110uro (Gjuro) |title=[[Croatian Encyclopedia]] |year=1999\u20132009 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some opinions, in his later works such as ''O psihologiji bez du\u0161e'' and ''Monizam i kr\u0161\u0107anstvo'' (Rad JAZU, 1909, 176 and 178) Arnold has abandoned his earlier philosophical views. Others such as [[Pavao Vuk-Pavlovi\u0107]], [[Stjepan Mati\u010devi\u0107]] and [[Bla\u017eenka Despot]] however maintain that Arnold's philosophical view was uniform and consistent - spiritualist pluralism which doesn't completely exclude spiritualist [[monism]].<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nArnold is one of the founders of the Croatian philosophical terminology,<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/> having authored two influential high school textbooks (''Logika'' and ''Psihologija'') that were standard textbooks for more than thirty years.<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nAt Arnold's proposal, in 1896 the Pedagogical Seminar for theoretical and practical training of future secondary school teachers was founded at the Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb. As a teacher, organizer of educational system, the first Professor of Pedagogy at the Faculty of Philosophy and the first head of the Pedagogical Seminar, has influenced many generations of teachers.<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nArnold died in Zagreb.\n\n==Works==\nIn literature:\n* ''Izabrane pjesme'', 1899, Zagreb\n* ''\u010ceznu\u0107a i ma\u0161tanja i pjesme'', 1900\u20131907, Zagreb\n* ''S visina i dubina'', 1918, Zagreb\n* ''Izabrane pjesme'', 1923, Zagreb\n* ''Na pragu vje\u010dnosti'', 1935, Zagreb\n\nIn philosophy:\n* ''Etika i poviest'', 1879, Zagreb\n* ''Logika za srednja u\u010dili\u0161ta'', 1888<sup>1</sup>, 1923<sup>5</sup>, Zagreb\n* ''Psihologija za srednja u\u010dili\u0161ta'', 1893<sup>1</sup>, 1923<sup>7</sup>, Zagreb\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Ivan Trnski]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = President of ''[[Matica hrvatska]]''| years = 1902 \u2013 1908}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Oton Ku\u010dera]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Josip \u0160ilovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = {{0}}{{0}}Rector of the [[University of Zagreb]]{{0}}{{0}} | years = 1899 \u2013 1900}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Rudolf Vimer]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Duro}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Croatian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Croatian writers]]\n[[Category:Croatian ethicists]]\n[[Category:University of Zagreb faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Krapina]]\n[[Category:People from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Members of the Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:\u0110uro Arnold 1898 Povjest knji\u017eevnosti hrvatske i srpske.png|thumb|\u0110uro Arnold]]\n'''\u0110uro Arnold''' (24 March 1853 \u2013 22 February 1941) was a [[Croatia]]n writer and [[philosopher]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://proleksis.lzmk.hr/8207/ |contribution=Arnold, \u0110uro |title=[[Proleksis Encyclopedia]] |date=September 2013 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and study==\nArnold was born as the 19th of 24 children of Ivan, a [[tax gatherer]], and Sofija, n\u00e9e [[Vukani\u0107]]. His ancestors arrived from [[Switzerland]] during the [[French Revolution]].<ref name=\"HBL\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://hbl.lzmk.hr/clanak.aspx?id=856 |contribution=ARNOLD, \u0110uro |last=Flego |first=Vi\u0161nja |author-link=Vi\u0161nja Flego |last2=Kaminski |first2=Martin |author2-link=Martin Kaminski |title=[[Croatian Biographical Lexicon]] |year=1983 |volume=1 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref> He was born in [[Ivanec]] and spent his early childhood in [[Krapina]]. He attended [[primary school]] in [[Zagreb]], and high school in [[Vara\u017edin]] and Zagreb, where he graduated in 1873.\n\nIn 1874 he enrolled at the [[Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb]] majoring in [[philosophy]], with a minor in [[history]] and [[geography]]. During the [[Bosnian crisis]] he was recruited, and it was only in 1879 that he was hired as a professor in a Zagreb [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]]. In 1880 he was promoted as the first PhD in philosophy at the [[University of Zagreb]], with a thesis ''Ethics and history'' (''Etika i povijest''), which was published in 1879.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> He continued his studies at the universities of [[University of G\u00f6ttingen|G\u00f6ttingen]] (1880), Berlin and Paris (1881/1882).\n\n== Work ==\nSince 1889 he served as the Director of the Royal Teacher's School. In 1894 he was appointed as a professor extraordinarius, and since 1896 as the full professor of theoretical and practical philosophy and pedagogy at the [[Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb]]. He retired in 1923. He was the dean of the Faculty of Arts in the periods of 1898\u20131899, and 1912\u20131913, and also the rector of the [[University of Zagreb]] in the period 1899\u20131900.\n\nHe was appointed as a corresponding member of the [[Yugoslav Academy of Sciences and Arts]] in 1891, and as a full member in 1899. He served as the president of [[Matica hrvatska]] in 1902\u20131909. In 1892 he became an honorary member of the Croatian Pedagogic-Literary Society, in 1924 a member of the Society of the Brothers of the Croatian Dragon, and an [[honorary citizen]] of [[Krapina]].<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\n==Writer==\nAs a writer, his work is a continuation of Croatia's romantic poetry in the tradition of [[August \u0160enoa]] and [[Franjo Markovi\u0107]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/> His first appearance as a writer was the song ''Pri povratku'' (\"On the way back\", ''Vienac'', 1873, 49). He mostly published patriotic songs, romances and [[ballad]]s with themes from [[Croatian history]] and [[folklore]] (''Krapinske elegije'', ''Damjan Juda, knez dubrova\u010dki'', ''Kata Lovi\u0107eva'' etc.), as well as reflexive lyricism in publications such as [[Vienac]] (1873\u20131886, 1888\u20131891, 1893\u20131902 ), [[Hrvatska lipa]] (1875), [[Hrvatski dom]] (1876), [[Obzor]] (1898, 1900, 1901, 1904), [[Prosvjeta]] (1904\u20131913), [[Hrvatsko kolo]] (1905, 1906, 1908, 1930), [[Katoli\u010dki list]] (1906, 1915, 1916), [[Hrvatska smotra]] (1907\u20131910, 1933), [[Hrvatsko pravo]] (1908, 1924), [[Koledar hrvatskoga katoli\u010dkoga narodnoga \u0111a\u0161tva]] (1909, 1910), [[Serafinski perivoj]] (1909\u20131913), [[Knji\u017eevni prilog]] (1911, 1912, 1913\u20131915), [[Hrvatska (publication)|Hrvatska]] (1912, 1914, 1915), [[Hrvatska prosvjeta]] (1914\u20131918), [[Na\u0161a misao]] (1914, 1915 ), [[Jeka od Osijeka]] (1918, 1919), [[Vijenac]] (1923, 1925, 1927), [[Hrvatsko pravo]] (1924, 1925), [[Omladina]] (1924, 1925), [[Hranilovi\u0107eva spomenica]] (1925), [[Selo i grad]] (1928/1929, 1930, 1931), [[Hrvatski list]] (1939), [[Novo doba]] (1940) and others. He wrote a single short story ''Samo \u010detvrt sata'' (Vienac, 1880, 15\u201318).<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nHe signed his works in codes and pseudonyms: ''A.'', ''G. A.'', ''Gj. A.'', ''Gj. A-d'', ''Gj. Ar.'', ''O. D.'', ''R. R.'', ''Ivan\u010danin'', ''Georg Arnold''.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> He published several books of poems, and the poem ''Domovina'' has gained him popularity.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> His works were published in many anthologies, calendars and almanacs. The selection of his poetry was translated to [[Czech language|Czech]], [[Esperanto]], [[German language|German]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]] and [[Italian language|Italian]]. He expressed his views on literature in talks at the Matica hrvatska conferences: ''Umjetnost prema znanosti'', ''Mo\u017ee li umjetnost zamijeniti vjeru'', ''Jedinstvena hrvatska narodna kultura'' (Glas Matice hrvatske, 1906, 1908, 1909).<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\n==Philosopher==\nAs a philosopher, he was influenced by [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]], [[Johann Friedrich Herbart]] and [[Hermann Lotze]], representing the \"spiritualist positivism\" movement and the view that the knowledge of the world can be reached only by the combined efforts of [[science]], [[art]] and [[religion]].<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/>  He wrote on the fundamental questions of philosophy, which he defined as the science of \"final causes and purposes of being\".<ref>''Logika'', p. 40</ref>\n\nIn the treatise ''Zadnja bi\u0107a'' (\"Last beings\", Rad JAZU, 1888, 93 ) he conceived a world composed from the variety of simple, immutable soullike \"last beings\" that are connected by the feeling of touch and hierarchically arranged according to different levels of awareness, with absolute consciousness, the [[God]], occupying the peak of the hierarchy.<ref name=\"HBL\"/> According to Arnold, faith represents the supreme stronghold of a man and the basic principle of harmony of his spiritual functions.<ref name=\"HE\">{{citation |contribution-url=http://www.enciklopedija.hr/Natuknica.aspx?ID=3953 |contribution=Arnold, \u0110uro (Gjuro) |title=[[Croatian Encyclopedia]] |year=1999\u20132009 |publisher=[[Leksikografski zavod Miroslav Krle\u017ea]] |language=Croatian}}</ref>\n\nAccording to some opinions, in his later works such as ''O psihologiji bez du\u0161e'' and ''Monizam i kr\u0161\u0107anstvo'' (Rad JAZU, 1909, 176 and 178) Arnold has abandoned his earlier philosophical views. Others such as [[Pavao Vuk-Pavlovi\u0107]], [[Stjepan Mati\u010devi\u0107]] and [[Bla\u017eenka Despot]] however maintain that Arnold's philosophical view was uniform and consistent - spiritualist pluralism which doesn't completely exclude spiritualist [[monism]].<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nArnold is one of the founders of the Croatian philosophical terminology,<ref name=\"PROLEKSIS\"/> having authored two influential high school textbooks (''Logika'' and ''Psihologija'') that were standard textbooks for more than thirty years.<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nAt Arnold's proposal, in 1896 the Pedagogical Seminar for theoretical and practical training of future secondary school teachers was founded at the Faculty of Philosophy in Zagreb. As a teacher, organizer of educational system, the first Professor of Pedagogy at the Faculty of Philosophy and the first head of the Pedagogical Seminar, has influenced many generations of teachers.<ref name=\"HBL\"/>\n\nArnold died in Zagreb.\n\n==Works==\nIn literature:\n* ''Izabrane pjesme'', 1899, Zagreb\n* ''\u010ceznu\u0107a i ma\u0161tanja i pjesme'', 1900\u20131907, Zagreb\n* ''S visina i dubina'', 1918, Zagreb\n* ''Izabrane pjesme'', 1923, Zagreb\n* ''Na pragu vje\u010dnosti'', 1935, Zagreb\n\nIn philosophy:\n* ''Etika i poviest'', 1879, Zagreb\n* ''Logika za srednja u\u010dili\u0161ta'', 1888<sup>1</sup>, 1923<sup>5</sup>, Zagreb\n* ''Psihologija za srednja u\u010dili\u0161ta'', 1893<sup>1</sup>, 1923<sup>7</sup>, Zagreb\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-culture}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Ivan Trnski]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = President of ''[[Matica hrvatska]]''| years = 1902 \u2013 1908}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Oton Ku\u010dera]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Josip \u0160ilovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = {{0}}{{0}}Rector of the [[University of Zagreb]]{{0}}{{0}} | years = 1899 \u2013 1900}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Rudolf Vimer]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arnold, Duro}}\n[[Category:1853 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Croatian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Croatian writers]]\n[[Category:Croatian ethicists]]\n[[Category:University of Zagreb faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Krapina]]\n[[Category:People from Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Members of the Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C4%90uro_Arnold"}
{"title_page": "Jack Copeland (surgeon)", "text_new": "{{short description|American cardiothoracic surgeon|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = Professor\n| name = Jack Copeland\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Jack Greene Copeland\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1942}} \n| birth_place = [[Roanoke, Virginia]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = \n| citizenship = \n| education = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = [[Heart transplantation]]\n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = [[Cardiothoracic surgeon]]\n| field = \n| work_institutions = *[[Banner University Medical Center Tucson|University of Arizona Medical Center (UAMC) in Tucson]]\n*[[University of California, San Diego]]\n| specialism = \n| research_field = *[[Artificial heart]]\n*[[Left ventricular assist device]]\n| notable_works = \n| prizes =  * 2001 Barney Clark Award \n*[[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation|ISHLT]] Past Pioneer Award 2013\n| child = 4\n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''Jack Greene Copeland''' (born 1942) is an American [[cardiothoracic surgeon]], who has established procedures in heart transplantation including repeat heart transplantation, the implantation of [[Artificial heart|total artificial hearts]] (TAH) to bridge the time to heart transplant, innovations in [[left ventricular assist device]]s (LVAD) and the technique of \"piggybacking\" a second heart (heterotopic heart transplant) in a person, while leaving them the original.\n\nIn 1985, he performed the first successful implant of the [[Jarvik 7]] artificial heart for the purpose of gaining time until a suitable heart donor could be found. The 25-year-old recipient received the heart transplant within two weeks of the implant and survived more than five years.\n\nCopeland co-founded [[SynCardia Systems]] and after being head of the cardiothoracic surgery programme at the [[Banner University Medical Center Tucson|University of Arizona Medical Center (UAMC) in Tucson]] for over thirty years, he moved to the [[University of California, San Diego]] in 2010.\n\nHe was one of the first presidents of the [[International Society of Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT), a society he helped co-found and who awarded him its Past Pioneer Award in 2013.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Stanford Campus Aerial Photo.JPG|thumb|Stanford Campus Aerial Photo]]\nJack Copeland was born in 1942 in [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]], Virginia<ref name=\"Eckholm1985\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/08/us/man-in-the-news-a-dedicated-heart-surgeon.html|title=Man in the news. A dedicated heart surgeon.|last=Eckholm|first=Erik|access-date=1 July 2018|language=en}}</ref> and is the son of a chemical engineer.<ref name=\"Wolmuth1986\"/> He entered [[Stanford University]] as a biology major in 1960, and subsequently earned a medical degree there nine years later. His interest in transplant surgery stemmed from his medical student days at Stanford, when he took up a job assisting in heart transplants in animals.<ref name=Eckholm1985/>\n\n==Early career==\nCopeland completed his internship and residency at the University Hospital of San Diego County, then assisted at the [[National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute]] at Bethesda, Maryland,<ref name=Eckholm1985/> where he reported on extended heart preservation outside the body,<ref name=Copeland1973>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=Jack|last2=Jones|first2=Michael|last3=Spragg|first3=Roger|last4=Stinson|first4=Edward|date=December 1973|title=In Vitro Preservation of Canine Hearts for 24 to 28 Hours Followed by Successful Orthotopic Transplantation|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=178|issue=6|pages=687\u2013692|pmc=1355830|pmid=4586264|doi=10.1097/00000658-197312000-00002}}</ref> before returning to Stanford. At Stanford, he became chief resident of cardiac surgery<ref name=Eckholm1985/> and in 1977 reported the first successful repeat-heart transplant in a human.<ref name=Copeland1977>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=J. G.|last2=Griepp|first2=R. B.|last3=Bieber|first3=C. P.|last4=Billingham|first4=M.|last5=Schroeder|first5=J. S.|last6=Hunt|first6=S.|last7=Mason|first7=J.|last8=Stinson|first8=E. B.|last9=Shumway|first9=N. E.|date=February 1977|title=Successful retransplantation of the human heart|journal=The Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery|volume=73|issue=2|pages=242\u2013247|issn=0022-5223|pmid=319302|doi=10.1016/s0022-5223(19)39953-2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rizvi|first=Syed-Saif Abbas|last2=Luc|first2=Jessica G. Y.|last3=Choi|first3=Jae Hwan|last4=Phan|first4=Kevin|last5=Moncho Escriv\u00e0|first5=Ester|last6=Patel|first6=Sinal|last7=Massey|first7=H. Todd|last8=Tchantchaleishvili|first8=Vakhtang|date=January 2018|title=Outcomes and survival following heart retransplantation for cardiac allograft failure: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=Annals of Cardiothoracic Surgery|volume=7|issue=1|pages=12\u201318|doi=10.21037/acs.2018.01.09|issn=2225-319X|pmc=5827127|pmid=29492380}}</ref>\n\nHe was inspired predominantly by heart surgeons [[Norman Shumway]] and [[Edward Stinson (surgeon)|Edward Stinson]] and he learned the technique of [[endomyocardial biopsy]] and interpretation of [[Billingham Criteria|organ rejection grading]] from cardiothoracic surgeon [[Philip Caves]] and pathologist [[Margaret Billingham]].<ref name=\"ISHLTInterview2010\">{{Citation|last=The International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation|title=Jack G. Copeland, MD|date=21 April 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvuPDXnUt1w|access-date=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Arizona hired Copeland in 1977<ref name=Eckholm1985/> and two years later he led the first heart transplant in Arizona.<ref name=\"tucson2010\">{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/news/local/education/college/ua-losing-copeland-star-of-heart-surgery/article_1909ad29-a564-58c9-ac14-e81ef1f653c3.html|title=UA losing Copeland, 'star' of heart surgery|last=Star|first=Becky Pallack Arizona Daily|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=1 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://heart.arizona.edu/sites/default/files/shc-fall-2009-55.pdf|title=Heart Transplant Program Celebrates 30-Year Anniversary|date=2009|work=The Sarver Heart Centre|access-date=|publisher=The University of Arizona College of Medicine|page=4}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982 Copeland stated that heart transplants were \"no longer consider[ed] \u2026 an experiment here. It has become a routine and predictable procedure\".<ref name=Eckholm1985/>\n\nAt Arizona, he was one of the first surgeons in the country to try the technique of \"piggybacking\" a second heart in a person, while leaving them the original,<ref name=Eckholm1985/> a procedure first performed by South African heart surgeon [[Christiaan Barnard]].<ref name=\"Stanford2004\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2004/october20/med-Heart-1020.html|title=Two hearts are better than one for toddler who undergoes historic operation|work=Stanford University|access-date=2 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy 1985, at the age 43, when he was head of the Cardiovascular and Thoracic Surgery Section at the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Tucson, his team had performed over sixty such transplants.<ref name=Eckholm1985/> In addition, in 1985, he performed Arizona's first combined [[heart-lung transplant]].{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n===The first bridge-to-transplant with a total artificial heart===\n[[File:JARVIK 7 artificial heart.jpg|thumb|JARVIK 7 TAH, used in 1985 as a bridge-to-transplant|alt=|200x200px]]\nIn 1985, Copeland and Mark Levinson with help from biomedical engineer Richard Smith, performed the first successful implant of the [[Jarvik 7]] total artificial heart, the early version of the SynCardia TAH, in 25-year-old grocery store clerk Michael Drummond who was suffering with severe [[heart failure]] due to [[cardiomyopathy]] and was awaiting a heart transplant.<ref name=\"Smith2015\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/thirty-years-ago-artificial-heart-helped-save-grocery-store-manager-180956388/|title=Thirty Years Ago, an Artificial Heart Helped Save a Grocery Store Manager|last=Wecker|first=Menachem|date=26 August 2015|work=Smithsonian|access-date=5 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cook2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Cook|first=Jason A.|last2=Shah|first2=Keyur B.|last3=Quader|first3=Mohammed A.|last4=Cooke|first4=Richard H.|last5=Kasirajan|first5=Vigneshwar|last6=Rao|first6=Kris K.|last7=Smallfield|first7=Melissa C.|last8=Tchoukina|first8=Inna|last9=Tang|first9=Daniel G.|date=December 2015|title=The total artificial heart|journal=Journal of Thoracic Disease|volume=7|issue=12|pages=2172\u20132180|doi=10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2015.10.70|issn=2072-1439|pmc=4703693|pmid=26793338}}</ref><ref name=\"ISHLTAward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/ishlt/media/documents/ISHLTPioneerAward_2013Recipient_JackCopeland.pdf|title=Pioneer Awards|website=www.ISHLT.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref> It was the first time this procedure was performed successfully as a temporary measure to buy time until a matching donor heart could be found.<ref name=\"ISHLTAward\"/> The previous TAH implants were temporary by Cooley (1969 and 1981) and Copeland (1985) had failed to result in survival for more than days and several were \"permanent\" TAH implants by [[William DeVries]] (Barney Clark in December 1982) that resulted in short term survival.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1985/03/08/tucson-patient-given-new-heart/439e5f06-5f00-4fd2-a575-7bb8bf853447/|title=Tucson Patient Given New Heart|last=Russell|first=Christine|date=8 March 1985|work=The Washington Post|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the first success, in March 1985, Copeland and his team had emergently implanted the unapproved Phoenix total artificial heart in a critically ill young man.  The [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] policy of making exceptions for unapproved devices use in true emergencies followed this case. The Michael Drummond case followed in August 1985. Worsening of Drummond's condition created a desperation for action and the decision to use a TAH. It allowed time to find a matching donor heart. He survived more than five years, having received his heart transplant within two weeks of the implant. His cause of death was [[lymphoma]].<ref name=\"ISHLTInterview2010\"/><ref name=\"Cook2015\"/>\n\nCopeland, along with [[Don B. Olsen]], was instrumental in forming CardioWest Technologies and continuing the research and development of TAH technology and its role in bridging-to-heart transplant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unews.utah.edu/utah-artificial-heart-pioneer-dies/|title=Utah artificial heart pioneer dies {{!}} UNews|website=unews.utah.edu|language=English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> Following FDA approval to trial the CardioWest TAH, he published his ten-year trial (1993\u20132002), assessing the performance of the TAH in just less than 100 people with [[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|class IV]] [[biventricular heart failure]] and at risk of imminent death. All included in the trial were eligible for transplant but were waiting for donors. The trial demonstrated better clinical outcomes when the TAH was used to bridge-to-transplant.<ref name=\"McKellar2018_p235\">{{cite book|last=McKellar|first=Shelley |title=Artificial Hearts: The Allure and Ambivalence of a Controversial Medical Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XCZEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA253|year=2018|publisher=Johns\u00a0Hopkins University |isbn=978-1421423555|pages=251\u2013253}}</ref>\u00a0In 2001, he co-founded [[SynCardia Systems]] which acquired CardioWest Technologies. In 2004, the SynCardia heart was granted FDA approval for use as a bridge-to-transplant.  It is the only TAH to obtain FDA approval and be commercially available.<ref name=Linkedin>{{Cite web|url=https://mu.linkedin.com/in/jack-copeland-46093528|title=Jack G. Copeland|website=Linkedin|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"McKellar2018_p315\">{{cite book|author=Shelley McKellar|title=Artificial Hearts: The Allure and Ambivalence of a Controversial Medical Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XCZEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA315|year=2018|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-1-4214-2355-5|page=315}}</ref><ref name=\"Draper2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearable-technologies.com/2018/10/syncardia-temporary-total-artificial-heart-shows-clear-life-saving-efficiency-study/|title=SynCardia Temporary Total Artificial Heart Shows Clear Life-Saving Efficiency: Study|last=Draper|first=Sam|date=16 October 2018|website=Wearable Technologies|language=English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other cardiac surgery===\nIn 2000, he performed America's first implant of a paediatric ventricular assist device.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} In 2010, he and his team also reported their results of using LVADs in infants and children with severe heart failure from [[dilated cardiomyopathy]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zimmerman|first=Hannah|last2=Covington|first2=Diane|last3=Smith|first3=Richard|last4=Copeland|first4=Jack|date=September 2010|title=Mechanical support and medical therapy reverse heart failure in infants and children|journal=Artificial Organs|volume=34|issue=11|pages=885\u2013890|doi=10.1111/j.1525-1594.2010.01069.x|issn=1525-1594|pmid=20636444}}</ref>\n\nOther procedures he has led include heart valve surgery, [[cardiac bypass surgery]] in adults and the repair of [[congenital heart defects]] in infants.<ref name=\"csheart\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kDwoAQAAIAAJ&q=copeland+repair+congenital+heart+defects+children&dq=copeland+repair+congenital+heart+defects+children|title=The New York Times Biographical Service|date=1985|publisher=New York Times & Arno Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n[[File:Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center.jpg|thumb|Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center]]\nHe resigned from the University of\u00a0Arizona\u00a0in 2010 after heading its Cardiovascular and Thoracic Surgery Section for over thirty years<ref name=\"csheart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csheart.com/Speakers/Detail/271|title=Speaker Detail|website=www.csheart.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2018}}\n</ref> and subsequently moved to San Diego, where his wife was completing her general surgery training.<ref name=tucson2010/> Here, he joined the faculty at the new [[Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center|Sulpizio Family Cardiovascular Center]] at the University of California, San Diego.<ref name=\"Gonzales2010\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/stories/2010/06/28/daily25.html|title=Artificial heart pioneer Jack Copeland leaving UA|website=www.bizjournals.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First FDA approved total artificial heart===\n[[File:The SynCardia temporary Total Artificial Heart with pink heart background.jpg|thumb|The SynCardia temporary Total Artificial Heart|alt=|243x243px]]\nOn 7 January 2011, during a four-hour operation, Copeland was part of the team that implanted, as a bridge-to-transplant, the world's only FDA-approved total [[artificial heart]] (TAH) for temporary use.<ref name=ucsdnewsJan2011>{{Cite web|url=https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/health/01-24ArtificialHeart.asp|title=First Total Artificial Heart Implanted in California at UC San Diego Medical Center|website=ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Heterotopic heart transplant at California===\nOn 13 February 2011, Copeland and his team at the UC San Diego Center for Transplantation, performed the rare \"piggyback\" heart operation again, resulting in a man having two beating hearts in his chest. Termed a heterotopic heart transplantation, recipient Smith received a donor heart while still keeping his own diseased heart. The alternative option, which would have required two operations, was to offer a [[Left ventricular assist device]] (LVAD) as a bridge-to-transplantation.<ref name=ucsdnewsFeb2011>{{Cite web|url=https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/health/02-18ValentineGift.asp|title=Two Hearts Beat as One|website=ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe procedure involved placing the new donor heart on the right side of Smith's own heart and then surgically joining the left [[Atrium (heart)|atria]] of both hearts to each other to allow oxygenated blood to flow direct from Smith's heart to the donor heart. The new heart's better functioning left [[ventricle (heart)|ventricle]] then pumped blood into the [[aorta]]. The patient's own right heart continued to pump blood through the lungs.<ref name=ucsdnewsFeb2011/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nCopeland was one of the co-founders of the [[International Society of Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT) in 1981. In addition, he served as one of the society's first presidents.<ref name=ISHLTAwardCopeland>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/ishlt/media/documents/ISHLTPioneerAward_2013Recipient_JackCopeland.pdf|title=Pioneer Awards|website=www.ISHLT.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn acknowledgment of his achievements with artificial hearts and heart-assist devices, he received the 2001 [[Barney Clark (patient)|Barney Clark Award]].<ref name=\"Martinez2001\">{{Cite web|url=https://opa.uahs.arizona.edu/newsroom/news/2001/dr-jack-copeland-receives-national-award-work-heart-devices|title=Dr. Jack Copeland Receives National Award for Work with Heart Devices {{!}} UAHS Office of Public Affairs|website=opa.uahs.arizona.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he received the ISHLT Past Pioneer Award.<ref name=\"ISHLTAward\"/>\n\n==Family==\nCopeland is married to Hannah Copeland a cardiac surgeon<ref name=missi>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umc.edu/news/News_Articles/2018/01/newest-transplant-surgeons-are-women-with-a-mission.html|title=Newest transplant surgeons women with a mission|website=University of Mississippi Medical Center|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> and has four children.<ref name=\"Wolmuth1986\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/for-transplant-specialists-jack-and-jan-copeland-home-is-where-the-hearts-are-vol-26-no-10/|title=For Transplant Specialists Jack and Jan Copeland, Home Is Where the Hearts Are|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\nHe has authored over 400 articles and presented nationally and internationally.<ref name=\"csheart\"/><ref name=\"Doximity\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.doximity.com/pub/jack-copeland-md-3315|title=Dr. Jack Copeland, MD \u2013 Ridgeland, MS {{!}} Thoracic Surgery on Doximity|website=Doximity|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n*{{cite journal | pmc = 1355830 | pmid=4586264 | doi=10.1097/00000658-197312000-00002 | volume=178 | title=In vitro preservation of canine hearts for 24 to 28 hours followed by successful orthotopic transplantation | year=1973 | journal=Ann Surg | pages=687\u201392 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG | last2 = Jones | first2 = M | last3 = Spragg | first3 = R | last4 = Stinson | first4 = EB}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 319302 | doi=10.1016/s0022-5223(19)39953-2 | volume=73 | title=Successful retransplantation of the human heart | year=1977 | journal=J Thorac Cardiovasc Surg | pages=242\u20137 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG | last2 = Griepp | first2 = RB | last3 = Bieber | first3 = CP | last4 = Billingham | first4 = M | last5 = Schroeder | first5 = JS | last6 = Hunt | first6 = S | last7 = Mason | first7 = J | last8 = Stinson | first8 = EB | last9 = Shumway | first9 = NE}}.\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/0011-3840(88)90007-X | volume=25 | title=Cardiac transplantation | year=1988 | journal=Current Problems in Surgery | pages=613\u2013672 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = Jack G.}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 3286040 | doi=10.1161/01.cir.77.6.1324 | volume=77 | title=Improvement in early saphenous vein graft patency after coronary artery bypass surgery with antiplatelet therapy: results of a Veterans Administration Cooperative Study | year=1988 | journal=Circulation | pages=1324\u201332 | last1 = Goldman | first1 = S | last2 = Copeland | first2 = J | last3 = Moritz | first3 = T | last4 = Henderson | first4 = W | last5 = Zadina | first5 = K | last6 = Ovitt | first6 = T | last7 = Doherty | first7 = J | last8 = Read | first8 = R | last9 = Chesler | first9 = E | last10 = Sako | first10 = Y}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 10171706 | doi=10.1300/J080v05n01_02 | volume=5 | title=Transplantation: a team approach. The chaplain's role: a cardiac surgeon's view | year=1993 | journal=J Health Care Chaplain | pages=5\u201310  | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 8719447 | volume=14 | title=Only optimal donors should be accepted for heart transplantation: protagonist | year=1995 | journal=J Heart Lung Transplant | pages=1038\u201342 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG}}.\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1016/S0003-4975(00)02268-2 | volume=71 | title=Bridge to transplantation with a thoratec left ventricular assist device in a 17-kg child | year=2001 | journal=The Annals of Thoracic Surgery | pages=1003\u20131004 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = Jack G | last2 = Arabia | first2 = Francisco A | last3 = Smith | first3 = Richard G}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 15329423 | doi=10.1056/NEJMoa040186 | volume=351 | title=Cardiac replacement with a total artificial heart as a bridge to transplantation | year=2004 | journal=N Engl J Med | pages=859\u201367 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG | last2 = Smith | first2 = RG | last3 = Arabia | first3 = FA | last4 = Nolan | first4 = PE | last5 = Sethi | first5 = GK | last6 = Tsau | first6 = PH | last7 = McClellan | first7 = D | last8 = Slepian | first8 = MJ}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 20636444 | doi=10.1111/j.1525-1594.2010.01069.x | volume=34 | title=Mechanical support and medical therapy reverse heart failure in infants and children | year=2010 | journal=Artif Organs | pages=885\u201390 | last1 = Zimmerman | first1 = H | last2 = Covington | first2 = D | last3 = Smith | first3 = R | last4 = Copeland | first4 = J}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 20636444 | doi=10.1111/j.1525-1594.2010.01069.x | volume=34 | title=Mechanical support and medical therapy reverse heart failure in infants and children | year=2010 | journal=Artif Organs | pages=885\u201390  | last1 = Zimmerman | first1 = H | last2 = Covington | first2 = D | last3 = Smith | first3 = R | last4 = Copeland | first4 = J}}.\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 24391330 | volume=40 | title=SynCardia Total Artificial Heart: update and future | pmc=3853833 | year=2013 | journal=Tex Heart Inst J | pages=587\u20138 | last1 = Copeland | first1 = JG}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jack_Copeland ResearchGate, Jack G. Copeland].\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvuPDXnUt1w ISHLT Interview with Jack G. Copeland, 2010].\n*[https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ipg602/documents/overview-2 Interventional procedure overview of artificial heart implantation as a bridge to transplantation for end-stage refractory biventricular heart failure (NICE)] (2017)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Copeland, Jack (surgeon)}}\n[[Category:American transplant surgeons]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Roanoke County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n[[Category:History of transplant surgery]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American cardiothoracic surgeon|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n| honorific_prefix = Professor\n| name = Jack Copeland\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Jack Greene Copeland\n| birth_date = {{birth year and age|1942}} \n| birth_place = [[Roanoke, Virginia]]\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date)  -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| nationality = \n| citizenship = \n| education = [[Stanford University]]\n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = [[Heart transplantation]]\n| relations = \n| website = \n| profession = [[Cardiothoracic surgeon]]\n| field = \n| work_institutions = *[[Banner University Medical Center Tucson|University of Arizona Medical Center (UAMC) in Tucson]]\n*[[University of California, San Diego]]\n| specialism = \n| research_field = *[[Artificial heart]]\n*[[Left ventricular assist device]]\n| notable_works = \n| prizes =  * 2001 Barney Clark Award \n*[[International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation|ISHLT]] Past Pioneer Award 2013\n| child = 4\n| module2 = \n| signature = \n}}\n'''Jack Greene Copeland''' (born 1942) is an American [[cardiothoracic surgeon]], who has established procedures in heart transplantation including repeat heart transplantation, the implantation of [[Artificial heart|total artificial hearts]] (TAH) to bridge the time to heart transplant, innovations in [[left ventricular assist device]]s (LVAD) and the technique of \"piggybacking\" a second heart (heterotopic heart transplant) in a person, while leaving them the original.\n\nIn 1985, he performed the first successful implant of the [[Jarvik 7]] artificial heart for the purpose of gaining time until a suitable heart donor could be found. The 25-year-old recipient received the heart transplant within two weeks of the implant and survived more than five years.\n\nCopeland co-founded [[SynCardia Systems]] and after being head of the cardiothoracic surgery programme at the [[Banner University Medical Center Tucson|University of Arizona Medical Center (UAMC) in Tucson]] for over thirty years, he moved to the [[University of California, San Diego]] in 2010.\n\nHe was one of the first presidents of the [[International Society of Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT), a society he helped co-found and who awarded him its Past Pioneer Award in 2013.\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Stanford Campus Aerial Photo.JPG|thumb|Stanford Campus Aerial Photo]]\nJack Copeland was born in 1942 in [[Roanoke, Virginia|Roanoke]], Virginia<ref name=\"Eckholm1985\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/08/us/man-in-the-news-a-dedicated-heart-surgeon.html|title=Man in the news. A dedicated heart surgeon.|last=Eckholm|first=Erik|access-date=1 July 2018|language=en}}</ref> and is the son of a chemical engineer.<ref name=\"Wolmuth1986\"/> He entered [[Stanford University]] as a biology major in 1960, and subsequently earned a medical degree there nine years later. His interest in transplant surgery stemmed from his medical student days at Stanford, when he took up a job assisting in heart transplants in animals.<ref name=Eckholm1985/>\n\n==Early career==\nCopeland completed his internship and residency at the University Hospital of San Diego County, then assisted at the [[National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute]] at Bethesda, Maryland,<ref name=Eckholm1985/> where he reported on extended heart preservation outside the body,<ref name=Copeland1973>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=Jack|last2=Jones|first2=Michael|last3=Spragg|first3=Roger|last4=Stinson|first4=Edward|date=December 1973|title=In Vitro Preservation of Canine Hearts for 24 to 28 Hours Followed by Successful Orthotopic Transplantation|journal=Annals of Surgery|volume=178|issue=6|pages=687\u2013692|pmc=1355830|pmid=4586264|doi=10.1097/00000658-197312000-00002}}</ref> before returning to Stanford. At Stanford, he became chief resident of cardiac surgery<ref name=Eckholm1985/> and in 1977 reported the first successful repeat-heart transplant in a human.<ref name=Copeland1977>{{Cite journal|last=Copeland|first=J. G.|last2=Griepp|first2=R. B.|last3=Bieber|first3=C. P.|last4=Billingham|first4=M.|last5=Schroeder|first5=J. S.|last6=Hunt|first6=S.|last7=Mason|first7=J.|last8=Stinson|first8=E. B.|last9=Shumway|first9=N. E.|date=February 1977|title=Successful retransplantation of the human heart|journal=The Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery|volume=73|issue=2|pages=242\u2013247|issn=0022-5223|pmid=319302|doi=10.1016/s0022-5223(19)39953-2}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rizvi|first=Syed-Saif Abbas|last2=Luc|first2=Jessica G. Y.|last3=Choi|first3=Jae Hwan|last4=Phan|first4=Kevin|last5=Moncho Escriv\u00e0|first5=Ester|last6=Patel|first6=Sinal|last7=Massey|first7=H. Todd|last8=Tchantchaleishvili|first8=Vakhtang|date=January 2018|title=Outcomes and survival following heart retransplantation for cardiac allograft failure: a systematic review and meta-analysis|journal=Annals of Cardiothoracic Surgery|volume=7|issue=1|pages=12\u201318|doi=10.21037/acs.2018.01.09|issn=2225-319X|pmc=5827127|pmid=29492380}}</ref>\n\nHe was inspired predominantly by heart surgeons [[Norman Shumway]] and [[Edward Stinson (surgeon)|Edward Stinson]] and he learned the technique of [[endomyocardial biopsy]] and interpretation of [[Billingham Criteria|organ rejection grading]] from cardiothoracic surgeon [[Philip Caves]] and pathologist [[Margaret Billingham]].<ref name=\"ISHLTInterview2010\">{{Citation|last=The International Society for Heart and Lung Transplantation|title=Jack G. Copeland, MD|date=21 April 2010|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvuPDXnUt1w|access-date=4 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe University of Arizona hired Copeland in 1977<ref name=Eckholm1985/> and two years later he led the first heart transplant in Arizona.<ref name=\"tucson2010\">{{Cite news|url=https://tucson.com/news/local/education/college/ua-losing-copeland-star-of-heart-surgery/article_1909ad29-a564-58c9-ac14-e81ef1f653c3.html|title=UA losing Copeland, 'star' of heart surgery|last=Star|first=Becky Pallack Arizona Daily|work=Arizona Daily Star|access-date=1 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://heart.arizona.edu/sites/default/files/shc-fall-2009-55.pdf|title=Heart Transplant Program Celebrates 30-Year Anniversary|date=2009|work=The Sarver Heart Centre|access-date=|publisher=The University of Arizona College of Medicine|page=4}}</ref>\n\nIn 1982 Copeland stated that heart transplants were \"no longer consider[ed] \u2026 an experiment here. It has become a routine and predictable procedure\".<ref name=Eckholm1985/>\n\nAt Arizona, he was one of the first surgeons in the country to try the technique of \"piggybacking\" a second heart in a person, while leaving them the original,<ref name=Eckholm1985/> a procedure first performed by South African heart surgeon [[Christiaan Barnard]].<ref name=\"Stanford2004\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.stanford.edu/news/2004/october20/med-Heart-1020.html|title=Two hearts are better than one for toddler who undergoes historic operation|work=Stanford University|access-date=2 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy 1985, at the age 43, when he was head of the Cardiovascular and Thoracic Surgery Section at the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Tucson, his team had performed over sixty such transplants.<ref name=Eckholm1985/> In addition, in 1985, he performed Arizona's first combined [[heart-lung transplant]].{{citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\n===The first bridge-to-transplant with a total artificial heart===\n[[File:JARVIK 7 artificial heart.jpg|thumb|JARVIK 7 TAH, used in 1985 as a bridge-to-transplant|alt=|200x200px]]\nIn 1985, Copeland and Mark Levinson with help from biomedical engineer Richard Smith, performed the first successful implant of the [[Jarvik 7]] total artificial heart, the early version of the SynCardia TAH, in 25-year-old grocery store clerk Michael Drummond who was suffering with severe [[heart failure]] due to [[cardiomyopathy]] and was awaiting a heart transplant.<ref name=\"Smith2015\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smithsonian-institution/thirty-years-ago-artificial-heart-helped-save-grocery-store-manager-180956388/|title=Thirty Years Ago, an Artificial Heart Helped Save a Grocery Store Manager|last=Wecker|first=Menachem|date=26 August 2015|work=Smithsonian|access-date=5 November 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"Cook2015\">{{Cite journal|last=Cook|first=Jason A.|last2=Shah|first2=Keyur B.|last3=Quader|first3=Mohammed A.|last4=Cooke|first4=Richard H.|last5=Kasirajan|first5=Vigneshwar|last6=Rao|first6=Kris K.|last7=Smallfield|first7=Melissa C.|last8=Tchoukina|first8=Inna|last9=Tang|first9=Daniel G.|date=December 2015|title=The total artificial heart|journal=Journal of Thoracic Disease|volume=7|issue=12|pages=2172\u20132180|doi=10.3978/j.issn.2072-1439.2015.10.70|issn=2072-1439|pmc=4703693|pmid=26793338}}</ref><ref name=\"ISHLTAward\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/ishlt/media/documents/ISHLTPioneerAward_2013Recipient_JackCopeland.pdf|title=Pioneer Awards|website=www.ISHLT.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref> It was the first time this procedure was performed successfully as a temporary measure to buy time until a matching donor heart could be found.<ref name=\"ISHLTAward\"/> The previous TAH implants were temporary by Cooley (1969 and 1981) and Copeland (1985) had failed to result in survival for more than days and several were \"permanent\" TAH implants by [[William DeVries]] (Barney Clark in December 1982) that resulted in short term survival.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1985/03/08/tucson-patient-given-new-heart/439e5f06-5f00-4fd2-a575-7bb8bf853447/|title=Tucson Patient Given New Heart|last=Russell|first=Christine|date=8 March 1985|work=The Washington Post|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the first success, in March 1985, Copeland and his team had emergently implanted the unapproved Phoenix total artificial heart in a critically ill young man.  The [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] policy of making exceptions for unapproved devices use in true emergencies followed this case. The Michael Drummond case followed in August 1985. Worsening of Drummond's condition created a desperation for action and the decision to use a TAH. It allowed time to find a matching donor heart. He survived more than five years, having received his heart transplant within two weeks of the implant. His cause of death was [[lymphoma]].<ref name=\"ISHLTInterview2010\"/><ref name=\"Cook2015\"/>\n\nCopeland, along with [[Don B. Olsen]], was instrumental in forming CardioWest Technologies and continuing the research and development of TAH technology and its role in bridging-to-heart transplant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unews.utah.edu/utah-artificial-heart-pioneer-dies/|title=Utah artificial heart pioneer dies {{!}} UNews|website=unews.utah.edu|language=English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> Following FDA approval to trial the CardioWest TAH, he published his ten-year trial (1993\u20132002), assessing the performance of the TAH in just less than 100 people with [[New York Heart Association Functional Classification|class IV]] [[biventricular heart failure]] and at risk of imminent death. All included in the trial were eligible for transplant but were waiting for donors. The trial demonstrated better clinical outcomes when the TAH was used to bridge-to-transplant.<ref name=\"McKellar2018_p235\">{{cite book|last=McKellar|first=Shelley |title=Artificial Hearts: The Allure and Ambivalence of a Controversial Medical Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XCZEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA253|year=2018|publisher=Johns\u00a0Hopkins University |isbn=978-1421423555|pages=251\u2013253}}</ref>\u00a0In 2001, he co-founded [[SynCardia Systems]] which acquired CardioWest Technologies. In 2004, the SynCardia heart was granted FDA approval for use as a bridge-to-transplant.  It is the only TAH to obtain FDA approval and be commercially available.<ref name=Linkedin>{{Cite web|url=https://mu.linkedin.com/in/jack-copeland-46093528|title=Jack G. Copeland|website=Linkedin|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"McKellar2018_p315\">{{cite book|author=Shelley McKellar|title=Artificial Hearts: The Allure and Ambivalence of a Controversial Medical Technology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XCZEDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA315|year=2018|publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-1-4214-2355-5|page=315}}</ref><ref name=\"Draper2018\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wearable-technologies.com/2018/10/syncardia-temporary-total-artificial-heart-shows-clear-life-saving-efficiency-study/|title=SynCardia Temporary Total Artificial Heart Shows Clear Life-Saving Efficiency: Study|last=Draper|first=Sam|date=16 October 2018|website=Wearable Technologies|language=English|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Other cardiac surgery===\nIn 2000, he performed America's first implant of a paediatric ventricular assist device.{{citation needed|date=July 2019}} In 2010, he and his team also reported their results of using LVADs in infants and children with severe heart failure from [[dilated cardiomyopathy]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Zimmerman|first=Hannah|last2=Covington|first2=Diane|last3=Smith|first3=Richard|last4=Copeland|first4=Jack|date=September 2010|title=Mechanical support and medical therapy reverse heart failure in infants and children|journal=Artificial Organs|volume=34|issue=11|pages=885\u2013890|doi=10.1111/j.1525-1594.2010.01069.x|issn=1525-1594|pmid=20636444}}</ref>\n\nOther procedures he has led include heart valve surgery, [[cardiac bypass surgery]] in adults and the repair of [[congenital heart defects]] in infants.<ref name=\"csheart\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=kDwoAQAAIAAJ&q=copeland+repair+congenital+heart+defects+children&dq=copeland+repair+congenital+heart+defects+children|title=The New York Times Biographical Service|date=1985|publisher=New York Times & Arno Press|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n[[File:Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center.jpg|thumb|Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center]]\nHe resigned from the University of\u00a0Arizona\u00a0in 2010 after heading its Cardiovascular and Thoracic Surgery Section for over thirty years<ref name=\"csheart\">{{cite web|url=http://www.csheart.com/Speakers/Detail/271|title=Speaker Detail|website=www.csheart.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 November 2018}}\n</ref> and subsequently moved to San Diego, where his wife was completing her general surgery training.<ref name=tucson2010/> Here, he joined the faculty at the new [[Sulpizio Cardiovascular Center|Sulpizio Family Cardiovascular Center]] at the University of California, San Diego.<ref name=\"Gonzales2010\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/stories/2010/06/28/daily25.html|title=Artificial heart pioneer Jack Copeland leaving UA|website=www.bizjournals.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=5 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===First FDA approved total artificial heart===\n[[File:The SynCardia temporary Total Artificial Heart with pink heart background.jpg|thumb|The SynCardia temporary Total Artificial Heart|alt=|243x243px]]\nOn 7 January 2011, during a four-hour operation, Copeland was part of the team that implanted, as a bridge-to-transplant, the world's only FDA-approved total [[artificial heart]] (TAH) for temporary use.<ref name=ucsdnewsJan2011>{{Cite web|url=https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/health/01-24ArtificialHeart.asp|title=First Total Artificial Heart Implanted in California at UC San Diego Medical Center|website=ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Heterotopic heart transplant at California===\nOn 13 February 2011, Copeland and his team at the UC San Diego Center for Transplantation, performed the rare \"piggyback\" heart operation again, resulting in a man having two beating hearts in his chest. Termed a heterotopic heart transplantation, recipient Smith received a donor heart while still keeping his own diseased heart. The alternative option, which would have required two operations, was to offer a [[Left ventricular assist device]] (LVAD) as a bridge-to-transplantation.<ref name=ucsdnewsFeb2011>{{Cite web|url=https://ucsdnews.ucsd.edu/archive/newsrel/health/02-18ValentineGift.asp|title=Two Hearts Beat as One|website=ucsdnews.ucsd.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe procedure involved placing the new donor heart on the right side of Smith's own heart and then surgically joining the left [[Atrium (heart)|atria]] of both hearts to each other to allow oxygenated blood to flow direct from Smith's heart to the donor heart. The new heart's better functioning left [[ventricle (heart)|ventricle]] then pumped blood into the [[aorta]]. The patient's own right heart continued to pump blood through the lungs.<ref name=ucsdnewsFeb2011/>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nCopeland was one of the co-founders of the [[International Society of Heart and Lung Transplantation]] (ISHLT) in 1981. In addition, he served as one of the society's first presidents.<ref name=ISHLTAwardCopeland>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ishlt.org/ishlt/media/documents/ISHLTPioneerAward_2013Recipient_JackCopeland.pdf|title=Pioneer Awards|website=www.ISHLT.org|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn acknowledgment of his achievements with artificial hearts and heart-assist devices, he received the 2001 [[Barney Clark (patient)|Barney Clark Award]].<ref name=\"Martinez2001\">{{Cite web|url=https://opa.uahs.arizona.edu/newsroom/news/2001/dr-jack-copeland-receives-national-award-work-heart-devices|title=Dr. Jack Copeland Receives National Award for Work with Heart Devices {{!}} UAHS Office of Public Affairs|website=opa.uahs.arizona.edu|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he received the ISHLT Past Pioneer Award.<ref name=\"ISHLTAward\"/>\n\n==Family==\nCopeland is married to Hannah Copeland a cardiac surgeon<ref name=missi>{{Cite web|url=https://www.umc.edu/news/News_Articles/2018/01/newest-transplant-surgeons-are-women-with-a-mission.html|title=Newest transplant surgeons women with a mission|website=University of Mississippi Medical Center|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2019}}</ref> and has four children.<ref name=\"Wolmuth1986\">{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/for-transplant-specialists-jack-and-jan-copeland-home-is-where-the-hearts-are-vol-26-no-10/|title=For Transplant Specialists Jack and Jan Copeland, Home Is Where the Hearts Are|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\nHe has authored over 400 articles and presented nationally and internationally.<ref name=\"csheart\"/><ref name=\"Doximity\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.doximity.com/pub/jack-copeland-md-3315|title=Dr. Jack Copeland, MD \u2013 Ridgeland, MS {{!}} Thoracic Surgery on Doximity|website=Doximity|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1355830/pdf/annsurg00250-0010.pdf  \u201cIn vitro preservation of canine hearts for 24 to 28 hours followed by successful orthotopic transplantation\u201d], co-authored with M Jones, R Spragg, and E B Stinson, ''Annals of Surgery'', December 1973, pp.&nbsp;687\u2013692.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/319302 \u201cSuccessful retransplantation of the human heart\u201d], co-authored with Griepp RB, Bieber CP, Billingham M, Schroeder JS, Hunt S, Mason J, Stinson EB, Shumway NE. ''Journal of Thoracic and Cardiovascular Surgery'', 1977 Feb;73(2):242-7, {{PMID|319302}}.\n*[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/001138408890007X \"Cardiac transplantation\"], ''[[Current Problems in Surgery]]'', 1988 Sep;25(9):607-72, {{doi|10.1016/0011-3840(88)90007-X}}.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3286040 \u201cImprovement in early saphenous vein graft patency after coronary artery bypass surgery with antiplatelet therapy: results of a Veterans Administration Cooperative Study\u201d], co-authored with Goldman S, Copeland J, Moritz T, Henderson W, Zadina K, Ovitt T, Doherty J, Read R, Chesler E, Sako Y, Circulation. 1988 Jun;77(6):1324\u201332, {{ PMID|3286040}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/10171706 \u201cTransplantation: a team approach. The chaplain's role: a cardiac surgeon's view\u201d], ''[[Journal of Health Care Chaplaincy]]'',\u00a01993;5(1\u20132):5\u201310. {{ DOI|10.1300/J080v05n01_02}}.\n*[https://www.annalsthoracicsurgery.org/article/0003-4975(94)90719-6/pdf \u201cFour-Year Experience With the CarboMedics Valve: The North American Experience\u201d], co-authored with G. K. Sethi, Ann Thorac Surg. 1994 Sep;58(3):630-7; discussion 637-8.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8719447 \"Only optimal donors should be accepted for heart transplantation: protagonist\"], ''[[Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation]]'', 1995 Nov\u2013Dec;14(6 Pt 1):1038\u201342, {{PMID|8719447}}.\n*[https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0003497500022682?via%3Dihub \u201cBridge to transplantation with a Thoratec left ventricular assist device in a 17-kg child\u201d], ''The Annals of Thoracic Surgery'', March 2001, Volume 71, Issue 3, pp.&nbsp;1003\u20131004.\n*[https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa040186?url_ver=Z39.88-2003&rfr_id=ori:rid:crossref.org&rfr_dat=cr_pub%3dwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov  \u201cCardiac Replacement with a Total Artificial Heart as a Bridge to Transplantation\u201d], co-authored with\u00a0Smith RG,\u00a0Arabia FA,\u00a0Nolan PE,\u00a0Sethi GK,\u00a0Tsau PH,\u00a0McClellan D,\u00a0Slepian MJ;\u00a0CardioWest Total Artificial Heart Investigators, ''[[New England Journal of Medicine]]'', 2004 Aug 26;351(9):859-67, {{PMID|15329423}}, {{DOI|10.1056/NEJMoa040186}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20636444 \"Mechanical support and medical therapy reverse heart failure in infants and children\"], co-authored with H. Zimmerman, D. Covington, R. Smith, ''Artificial Organs'', 2010 Nov;34(11):885-90. {{doi|10.1111/j.1525-1594.2010.01069.x}}.\n*[https://www.jhltonline.org/article/S1053-2498(17)31879-X/fulltext \u201cProfessor Christian Cabrol (1925 to 2017)\u201d], ''Journal of Heart and Lung Transplantation'', 2017 Sep;36(9):1023\u20131024. {{PMID|28720213}}, {{doi|10.1016/j.healun.2017.06.013.}}.\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3853833/ \"SynCardia Total Artificial Heart\"], ''Texas Heart Institute Journal'', 2013; 40(5): 587\u2013588, {{PMID|24391330}}.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jack_Copeland ResearchGate, Jack G. Copeland].\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jvuPDXnUt1w ISHLT Interview with Jack G. Copeland, 2010].\n*[https://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ipg602/documents/overview-2 Interventional procedure overview of artificial heart implantation as a bridge to transplantation for end-stage refractory biventricular heart failure (NICE)] (2017)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Copeland, Jack (surgeon)}}\n[[Category:American transplant surgeons]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Stanford University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Roanoke County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Virginia]]\n[[Category:History of heart surgery]]\n[[Category:History of transplant surgery]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSelected publications:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jack_Copeland_(surgeon)"}
